pr_title: Fix part of #9749: Migrate Admin page.
pr_body:
## Overview

1. This PR fixes part of #9749.
2. This PR does the following: Migrate Admin page.

## Essential Checklist

- [x] The PR title starts with "Fix #bugnum: ", followed by a short, clear summary of the changes. (If this PR fixes part of an issue, prefix the title with "Fix part of #bugnum: ...".)
- [x] The linter/Karma presubmit checks have passed locally on your machine.
- [x] "Allow edits from maintainers" is checked. (See [here](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) for instructions on how to enable it.)
  - This lets reviewers restart your CircleCI tests for you.
- [x] The PR is made from a branch that's **not** called "develop".

## Proof that changes are correct

admin-config-tab:

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/122652157-fa357000-d15a-11eb-8ac1-e7865202df85.mp4

admin-roles tab:

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/122652167-ff92ba80-d15a-11eb-9f3a-5c4130252057.mp4



## PR Pointers

- Make sure to follow the [instructions for making a code change](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Contributing-code-to-Oppia#instructions-for-making-a-code-change).
- Oppiabot will notify you when you don't add a PR_CHANGELOG label. If you are unable to do so, please @-mention a code owner (who will be in the Reviewers list), or ask on [Gitter](https://gitter.im/oppia/oppia-chat).
- For what code owners will expect, see the [Code Owner's wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Oppia%27s-code-owners-and-checks-to-be-carried-out-by-developers).
- Make sure your PR follows conventions in the [style guide](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Coding-style-guide), otherwise this will lead to review delays.
- Never force push. If you do, your PR will be closed.
- Oppiabot can assign anyone for review/help if you leave a comment like the following: "{{Question/comment}} @{{reviewer_username}} PTAL"
- Some of the e2e tests are flaky, and can fail for reasons unrelated to your PR. We are working on fixing this, but in the meantime, if you need to restart the tests, please check the ["If your build fails" wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/If-your-build-fails).

pr_body:
## Overview

1. This PR fixes #12386 and fixes part of #9749.
2. This PR does the following: Migrates base-content directive.

PR is open for some dependencies (top navigation bar, footer) of base-content.
So, I used upgradeComponent for that dependencies. If those PRs get merged before this, I will update this PR to use the migrated components.

## Essential Checklist

- [x] The PR title starts with "Fix #bugnum: ", followed by a short, clear summary of the changes. (If this PR fixes part of an issue, prefix the title with "Fix part of #bugnum: ...".)
- [x] The linter/Karma presubmit checks have passed locally on your machine.
- [x] "Allow edits from maintainers" is checked. (See [here](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) for instructions on how to enable it.)
  - This lets reviewers restart your CircleCI tests for you.
- [x] The PR is made from a branch that's **not** called "develop".

## Proof that changes are correct

base-content:

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/113178628-65faf180-926c-11eb-8e92-198e1bf0dee4.mp4


## PR Pointers

- Make sure to follow the [instructions for making a code change](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Contributing-code-to-Oppia#instructions-for-making-a-code-change).
- Oppiabot will notify you when you don't add a PR_CHANGELOG label. If you are unable to do so, please @-mention a code owner (who will be in the Reviewers list), or ask on [Gitter](https://gitter.im/oppia/oppia-chat).
- For what code owners will expect, see the [Code Owner's wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Oppia%27s-code-owners-and-checks-to-be-carried-out-by-developers).
- Make sure your PR follows conventions in the [style guide](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Coding-style-guide), otherwise this will lead to review delays.
- Never force push. If you do, your PR will be closed.
- Oppiabot can assign anyone for review/help if you leave a comment like the following: "{{Question/comment}} @{{reviewer_username}} PTAL"
- Some of the e2e tests are flaky, and can fail for reasons unrelated to your PR. We are working on fixing this, but in the meantime, if you need to restart the tests, please check the ["If your build fails" wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/If-your-build-fails).

pr_title: Fix part of #9749: Migrate Profile page.
pr_body:
## Overview

1. This PR fixes part of #9749.
2. This PR does the following: Migrate Profile page.

## Essential Checklist

- [x] The PR title starts with "Fix #bugnum: ", followed by a short, clear summary of the changes. (If this PR fixes part of an issue, prefix the title with "Fix part of #bugnum: ...".)
- [x] The linter/Karma presubmit checks have passed locally on your machine.
- [x] "Allow edits from maintainers" is checked. (See [here](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) for instructions on how to enable it.)
  - This lets reviewers restart your CircleCI tests for you.
- [x] The PR is made from a branch that's **not** called "develop".

## Proof that changes are correct


https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/121074995-3fb87b80-c7f2-11eb-9664-d3763072b338.mp4



## PR Pointers

- Make sure to follow the [instructions for making a code change](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Contributing-code-to-Oppia#instructions-for-making-a-code-change).
- Oppiabot will notify you when you don't add a PR_CHANGELOG label. If you are unable to do so, please @-mention a code owner (who will be in the Reviewers list), or ask on [Gitter](https://gitter.im/oppia/oppia-chat).
- For what code owners will expect, see the [Code Owner's wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Oppia%27s-code-owners-and-checks-to-be-carried-out-by-developers).
- Make sure your PR follows conventions in the [style guide](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Coding-style-guide), otherwise this will lead to review delays.
- Never force push. If you do, your PR will be closed.
- Oppiabot can assign anyone for review/help if you leave a comment like the following: "{{Question/comment}} @{{reviewer_username}} PTAL"
- Some of the e2e tests are flaky, and can fail for reasons unrelated to your PR. We are working on fixing this, but in the meantime, if you need to restart the tests, please check the ["If your build fails" wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/If-your-build-fails).

pr_title: Fix part of #9749: Migrate Preferences page
pr_body:
## Overview

1. This PR fixes part of #9749.
2. This PR does the following: Migrate preferences page.

## Essential Checklist

- [x] The PR title starts with "Fix #bugnum: ", followed by a short, clear summary of the changes. (If this PR fixes part of an issue, prefix the title with "Fix part of #bugnum: ...".)
- [x] The linter/Karma presubmit checks have passed locally on your machine.
- [x] "Allow edits from maintainers" is checked. (See [here](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) for instructions on how to enable it.)
  - This lets reviewers restart your CircleCI tests for you.
- [x] The PR is made from a branch that's **not** called "develop".

## Proof that changes are correct


https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/124273845-2939e180-db5e-11eb-9a1d-ee1981891b9c.mp4



## PR Pointers

- Make sure to follow the [instructions for making a code change](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Contributing-code-to-Oppia#instructions-for-making-a-code-change).
- Oppiabot will notify you when you don't add a PR_CHANGELOG label. If you are unable to do so, please @-mention a code owner (who will be in the Reviewers list), or ask on [Gitter](https://gitter.im/oppia/oppia-chat).
- For what code owners will expect, see the [Code Owner's wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Oppia%27s-code-owners-and-checks-to-be-carried-out-by-developers).
- Make sure your PR follows conventions in the [style guide](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Coding-style-guide), otherwise this will lead to review delays.
- Never force push. If you do, your PR will be closed.
- Oppiabot can assign anyone for review/help if you leave a comment like the following: "{{Question/comment}} @{{reviewer_username}} PTAL"
- Some of the e2e tests are flaky, and can fail for reasons unrelated to your PR. We are working on fixing this, but in the meantime, if you need to restart the tests, please check the ["If your build fails" wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/If-your-build-fails).

We will need to find a way to fix this in case a test we write in the future uses mat-select and actually expects scrolling to be done.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 6, 19, 25, 22, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'kevintab95', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 664821949, 'comment_body': 'oh! do we know why? In general, we try to avoid "browser.executeScript" where possible because it could introduce flakiness. So this should be a last resort.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 6, 19, 26, 27, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'kevintab95', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 664829798, 'comment_body': "The purpose of `getAttribute('innerHTML')` is to get contents of this attribute.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/124656613-10636000-debf-11eb-9445-0f6d3787e750.png)

It is not similiar to javascript `innerHTML` property on html element.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/124656763-3c7ee100-debf-11eb-8662-74125c220f1d.png)

This javascript property and html attribute are two different things for protractor.

It is returning null due to absence of innerHTML html attribute on base-container div element.

Earlier, there used to be a `getInnerHTML` function provided by protractor.
This was removed and browser.executeScript was the replacement.

https://github.com/angular/protractor/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md#breaking-changes-3

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/124657216-d9da1500-debf-11eb-9cad-7f32180e43cd.png)

", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 6, 19, 40, 37, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 664831767, 'comment_body': 'Proof:
test html file.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/124657676-72709500-dec0-11eb-8dac-620770e523da.png)

Test:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/124657714-7ef4ed80-dec0-11eb-96a7-8d044c3941f0.png)

This proves that `innerHTML` attribute and innerHTML javascript property behaves differently from each other.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 6, 19, 44, 8, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 664832469, 'comment_body': 'sure', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 6, 19, 45, 15, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 664833524, 'comment_body': 'Ah, I see. pr_title: Fix part of #9749, #8473: Migrate part of topic editor page.
pr_body:
## Overview

1. This PR fixes part of #9749, #8473.
2. This PR does the following: Migrate part of topic editor page.

Earlier each of the below-listed services and directives had their individual PR.
But most of them were blocked/stacked by each other.
So, merged into one PR.

Services:
1. Topic Editor State Service
2. Topic editor routing service
3. Subtopic validation service

Directives:
1. Topic editor navbar breadcrumb
2. Question difficulty selector

Tabs:
1. Subtopic preview tab
2. Topic preview tab

## Essential Checklist

pr_body:
## Overview


1. This fixes part of #9749.
2. This PR does the following: Migrate Preview thumbnail.

## Essential Checklist

- [x] The PR title starts with "Fix #bugnum: ", followed by a short, clear summary of the changes. (If this PR fixes part of an issue, prefix the title with "Fix part of #bugnum: ...".)
- [x] The linter/Karma presubmit checks have passed locally on your machine.
- [x] "Allow edits from maintainers" is checked. (See [here](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) for instructions on how to enable it.)
  - This lets reviewers restart your CircleCI tests for you.
- [x] The PR is made from a branch that's **not** called "develop".

## Proof that changes are correct

![Screenshot from 2021-05-23 02-02-46](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/119240636-91180800-bb6e-11eb-8333-dcc2f930c1ee.png)


## PR Pointers

- Make sure to follow the [instructions for making a code change](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Contributing-code-to-Oppia#instructions-for-making-a-code-change).
- Oppiabot will notify you when you don't add a PR_CHANGELOG label. If you are unable to do so, please @-mention a code owner (who will be in the Reviewers list), or ask on [Gitter](https://gitter.im/oppia/oppia-chat).
- For what code owners will expect, see the [Code Owner's wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Oppia%27s-code-owners-and-checks-to-be-carried-out-by-developers).
- Make sure your PR follows conventions in the [style guide](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Coding-style-guide), otherwise this will lead to review delays.
- Never force push. If you do, your PR will be closed.
- Oppiabot can assign anyone for review/help if you leave a comment like the following: "{{Question/comment}} @{{reviewer_username}} PTAL"
- Some of the e2e tests are flaky, and can fail for reasons unrelated to your PR. We are working on fixing this, but in the meantime, if you need to restart the tests, please check the ["If your build fails" wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/If-your-build-fails).

```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 19, 12, 21, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vojtechjelinek', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672276873, 'comment_body': 'done ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 19, 13, 2, 43, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672277839, 'comment_body': 'done', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 19, 13, 4, 5, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672478727, 'comment_body': 'Perhaps FRONTEND_ROUTES --> ROUTES_HANDLED_BY_FRONTEND might be clearer.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 19, 17, 6, 56, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'seanlip', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672479791, 'comment_body': "What if the page is a legitimate 404 -- what happens in the flow where the user goes to /abc (say)?

I'm a bit unclear about the difference between (a) route is not handled by Angular frontend but still exists in general, (b) route is invalid. Is (a) a possibility, and if not, why not?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 19, 17, 8, 28, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'seanlip', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672528053, 'comment_body': '**All the routes not registered at the backend are handled further by the angular router.**

![proposed_routing_system](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/126205645-eb91c013-53e8-4278-85c7-a2ad1baa79c8.png)

We cannot decide that a page is a legitimate 404 at the backend as it may be a case that route is not registered at the backend but is registered with angular router. So, for legitimate 404 the flow with direct to angular router, then angular check it with its own list of routes, and if it does not match it will lazy load the error module (page) and show it to the user.

I realize my mistake that I should have named the variable registered with angular router instead, as all routes which are not found on backend are redirected to angular router (so, in a sense it handle those too).

What the above code does is handling status code. For the legitimate 404 page, the status code will be set 404 and for the valid pages registered with angular router, it will be 200.

All the routes registered on the backend (handlers and pages not yet migrated to router) are not handled by the angular router, (a) case in your question.
(b) A invalid route is further redirected to angular router by rendering `oppia-root.mainpage.html` (unified entry point) and then the angular router will decide whether it is a valid page or a legitimate 404 route.

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/126206315-86620979-647f-4c8c-a779-3568fec17560.mp4

![image (2)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/126207985-c048cb26-eb6c-434d-b65c-9337a56264d9.png)
With the above code, status code for the routes in red box is 200 and for those matching green box (legitimate 404) is 404.
', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 19, 18, 21, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672529712, 'comment_body': 'I think ROUTES_REGISTERED_WITH_FRONTEND will be better.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 19, 18, 24, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672535974, 'comment_body': 'changed to `ROUTES_REGISTERED_WITH_FRONTEND`', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 7, 19, 18, 33, 39, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 672755443, 'comment_body': 'Thanks, @ashutoshc8101, I think I get it now. Instead, for such routes, it would be better to have them all result in 200 at the outset. pr_body:
## Overview

1. This PR fixes or fixes part of #9749
2. This PR does the following: Migrate library page.

Everything same as #13412 except this commit https://github.com/oppia/oppia/pull/13498/commits/8362f7adc2bc7f3107ccea1b9cc4b03699a1f158

Why #13412 caused typescript checks to fail:
https://github.com/oppia/oppia/pull/12989 got merged just 1 hour before and #13412 didn't had the changes from #12989 during merge.

## Essential Checklist

- [x] The PR title starts with "Fix #bugnum: ", followed by a short, clear summary of the changes. (If this PR fixes part of an issue, prefix the title with "Fix part of #bugnum: ...".)
- [x] The linter/Karma presubmit checks have passed locally on your machine.
- [x] "Allow edits from maintainers" is checked. (See [here](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) for instructions on how to enable it.)
  - This lets reviewers restart your CircleCI tests for you.
- [x] The PR is made from a branch that's **not** called "develop".

## Proof that changes are correct

https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/126032939-24e57e4a-e52b-4f24-8030-8ef6d132ae99.mp4


## PR Pointers

- Make sure to follow the [instructions for making a code change](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Contributing-code-to-Oppia#instructions-for-making-a-code-change).
- Oppiabot will notify you when you don't add a PR_CHANGELOG label. If you are unable to do so, please @-mention a code owner (who will be in the Reviewers list), or ask on [Gitter](https://gitter.im/oppia/oppia-chat).
- For what code owners will expect, see the [Code Owner's wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Oppia%27s-code-owners-and-checks-to-be-carried-out-by-developers).
- Make sure your PR follows conventions in the [style guide](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Coding-style-guide), otherwise this will lead to review delays.
- Never force push. If you do, your PR will be closed.
- Oppiabot can assign anyone for review/help if you leave a comment like the following: "{{Question/comment}} @{{reviewer_username}} PTAL"
- Some of the e2e tests are flaky, and can fail for reasons unrelated to your PR. We are working on fixing this, but in the meantime, if you need to restart the tests, please check the ["If your build fails" wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/If-your-build-fails).

## Overview

1. This PR fixes part of #9749.
2. This PR does the following: Migrate Signup Page.

## Essential Checklist

- [x] The PR title starts with "Fix #bugnum: ", followed by a short, clear summary of the changes. (If this PR fixes part of an issue, prefix the title with "Fix part of #bugnum: ...".)
- [x] The linter/Karma presubmit checks have passed locally on your machine.
- [x] "Allow edits from maintainers" is checked. (See [here](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) for instructions on how to enable it.)
  - This lets reviewers restart your CircleCI tests for you.
- [x] The PR is made from a branch that's **not** called "develop".

## Proof that changes are correct


https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/126137012-d2e90715-4a75-4e5f-80b5-2d267ed7ecb0.mp4



## PR Pointers

- Make sure to follow the [instructions for making a code change](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Contributing-code-to-Oppia#instructions-for-making-a-code-change).
- Oppiabot will notify you when you don't add a PR_CHANGELOG label. If you are unable to do so, please @-mention a code owner (who will be in the Reviewers list), or ask on [Gitter](https://gitter.im/oppia/oppia-chat).
- For what code owners will expect, see the [Code Owner's wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Oppia%27s-code-owners-and-checks-to-be-carried-out-by-developers).
- Make sure your PR follows conventions in the [style guide](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Coding-style-guide), otherwise this will lead to review delays.
- Never force push. If you do, your PR will be closed.
- Oppiabot can assign anyone for review/help if you leave a comment like the following: "{{Question/comment}} @{{reviewer_username}} PTAL"
- Some of the e2e tests are flaky, and can fail for reasons unrelated to your PR. We are working on fixing this, but in the meantime, if you need to restart the tests, please check the ["If your build fails" wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/If-your-build-fails).

pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 684891522, 'comment_body': "Can you explain what's `MANUALLY_REGISTERED_WITH_BACKEND` and why it is introduced? :) ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 9, 4, 5, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DubeySandeep', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 685146080, 'comment_body': "Some URLs contain URL fragments and they have different syntax for angular router and backend.
eg.
Url for backend: /learn/<classroom_url_fragment>
url for angular router: /learn/:classroom_url_fragment

So, I have used the second case in constant.ts (so, it works directly with the angular router).

And manually registered these routes with fragments in the backend.
That's why I am excluding these routes in this loop.

This explanation is for other pages with URL fragments in PR #13533.

For, /signup route, it does not use the common Handler `OppiaRootPage` unlike others. It uses SignupPageHandler as it performs additional checks too.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 9, 12, 23, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}]

    this.pageHeadService.updateTitleAndMetaTags(
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 2, 9, 19, 26, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'DubeySandeep', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 681000945, 'comment_body': 'Hmm, then I would probably go by the number of places/files where we need to do this kind of operation (addition/removal). Which I think will be more than the addition required.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 2, 17, 8, 52, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 681348500, 'comment_body': "Hmmm, if all of these are in one file then it might be fine, but I'm with any solution here.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 3, 0, 27, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vojtechjelinek', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682028138, 'comment_body': '@vojtechjelinek @brianrodri PTAL', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 3, 19, 7, 7, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682665358, 'comment_body': "I'm not against this change, but why is it needed now and wasn't before?", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 4, 14, 22, 50, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'vojtechjelinek', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682672019, 'comment_body': 'because they are no static pages in `app_dev.yaml` now and neither they are supposed to be there within future.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 4, 14, 29, 59, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682674389, 'comment_body': 'Earlier login and signup routes are registered with the app_dev.yaml, but they are migrated to the angular router now.
They are no `login-page.mainpage.html` or `signup-page.mainpage.html` now. The requests to the /login and /signup routes, go to the oppia-root.mainpage.html and then angular router decides which view to show based on the URL.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 4, 14, 32, 32, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682778325, 'comment_body': "So, just to be clear -- it is still technically possible for anyone to log in during maintenance mode, correct? They just can't do anything and will see a 503 immediately?

If so, this seems fine -- but I wanted to confirm that it's actually the post-PR behaviour. (Has this been tested manually? Would like to see a video of this in the PR description.) ", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 4, 16, 32, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'seanlip', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 682813736, 'comment_body': 'Present behaviour on develop:
Anyone can access the login page but only admins can access the functionality after logging in. Ordinary users will see a maintenance mode immediately after logging in. Maintenance page has a UI bug at present on develop. This PR also fixes that.

pr_title: Migrate more pages to angular router
pr_body: ## Overview 1. This PR fixes or fixes part of NA 2. This PR does the following: Migrate 10 more pages to angular router. Relevant Design Docs: Proposal Link Route Guard Implementation Doc Doc discussing PROs and CONS of route guards and internal validation This PR migrates following pages to the router: - Profile Page - Release Coordinator Page - Story Viewer Page - Classroom Page - Preferences Page - Splash Page - Pending Account Deletion Page - Delete Account Page - Stewards Landing Page - Library Page ## Essential Checklist - [ ] The PR title starts with "Fix #bugnum: ", followed by a short, clear summary of the changes. (If this PR fixes part of an issue, prefix the title with "Fix part of #bugnum: ...".) - [x] The linter/Karma presubmit checks have passed locally on your machine. - [x] "Allow edits from maintainers" is checked. (See [here](https://help.github.com/en/github/collaborating-with-issues-and-pull-requests/allowing-changes-to-a-pull-request-branch-created-from-a-fork) for instructions on how to enable it.) - This lets reviewers restart your CircleCI tests for you. - [x] The PR is made from a branch that's **not** called "develop". ## Proof that changes are correct 1. Profile, Preferences, Delete Account, Library And Classroom Pages: https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/128133019-0ab69662-285c-4666-9dc5-701fac047e07.mp4 2. Stewards Landing and Splash Pages: https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/128133090-356ac7c2-1cdf-4496-bb4b-6a7805aa9edb.mp4 3. Release Coordinator Page https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/128133109-bf6ce09d-719a-44f2-87e9-b52ed8f760eb.mp4 4. Story Viewer Page: https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/128133921-b5983356-3790-47ef-9ffd-19ac2c9d387d.mp4 5. Pending Account Deletion Page: https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/128133402-fc62a7ca-d511-4ed8-bb1b-746224874acf.mp4 ## PR Pointers - Make sure to follow the [instructions for making a code change](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Contributing-code-to-Oppia#instructions-for-making-a-code-change). - Oppiabot will notify you when you don't add a PR_CHANGELOG label. If you are unable to do so, please @-mention a code owner (who will be in the Reviewers list), or ask on [Gitter](https://gitter.im/oppia/oppia-chat). - For what code owners will expect, see the [Code Owner's wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Oppia%27s-code-owners-and-checks-to-be-carried-out-by-developers). - Make sure your PR follows conventions in the [style guide](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/Coding-style-guide), otherwise this will lead to review delays. - Never force push. If you do, your PR will be closed. - Oppiabot can assign anyone for review/help if you leave a comment like the following: "{{Question/comment}} @{{reviewer_username}} PTAL" - Some of the e2e tests are flaky, and can fail for reasons unrelated to your PR. We are working on fixing this, but in the meantime, if you need to restart the tests, please check the ["If your build fails" wiki page](https://github.com/oppia/oppia/wiki/If-your-build-fails).

validation and the subsequent action based on the result of the validation was done by the backend.
But now, the code for access_validation is present at the backend (`access_validation.py`), and code for subsequent action is placed in the frontend (route guards and internal validation). Both parts have their own unit tests (`access_validation_test.py` and frontend unit tests for route guards and page-root components`. So, the behaviour which was tested before cannot be tested in the backend as half of the functionality is moved to the frontend. But the subparts can be tested on the backend and frontend separately.

Example:
Earlier, there was a test in the backend which tests the behavior that the user is redirected to the preferred dashboard page if he is logged in and tries to reach the splash page.

Now, it is tested in the backend that access validation provides the preferred dashboard as JSON response and it is tested in the frontend that user is redirected to the preferred dashboard which is provided by the access validation handler.

That would also make the code more readable since the function name can explain what this code does", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 10, 14, 59, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'U8NWXD', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686110733, 'comment_body': 'The trigger for redirection changes with different scenarios (e.g. click on sign-in button, loading of logout page).

So, I had to give an option to provide the trigger and the same goes for the condition to detect redirection.

According to my observation, there is no duplication of callbacks.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 10, 15, 7, 38, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686114241, 'comment_body': "I used 10,000 ms by assuming that all pages should redirect in this time span. There is no other rationale behind this.
Please suggest if you have a better number.
Source for this approach: https://github.com/angular/protractor/blob/master/spec/withLoginConf.js

It is not written anywhere that this is the recommended approach but it is specified that client-side redirection will cause errors  here https://github.com/angular/protractor/issues/2643

I can explain what is the problem with the waitFor approach.

When the control reaches await `action.click('sign in button')`. It only waits for a click to happen but doesnot wait for javascript linked with a button to finish and it starts waiting (for angular/element on the page) on the current page (not on the new page after redirection).

So, there is a race condition between execution of `await waitFor.pageToFullyLoad` and `window.location.href`.
On high-speed environments, window.location.href (redirect) happens first and error is not encountered.
But on low-speed environments (like CI, I was able to increase flakiness by reducing memory of a test VM), the opposite occurs and we get a flake.

This explains why flake was only occurring on ci but not on my machine.

![New Project (6)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/128891284-742d997e-bfd5-4ee0-8210-cbd1b29154e5.png)

With the new approach, we explicitly wait for URL to change before continuing the suite:
![New Project (5)](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/24855641/128892183-c65efc97-c30b-45e1-b88a-a1b964f20e48.png)


", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 10, 15, 11, 42, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686298833, 'comment_body': 'waits --> wait', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 10, 20, 28, 12, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'seanlip', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686980916, 'comment_body': "> wait for all async tasks on new page to finish

This isn't what `pageToFullyLoad()` does. It only waits for full-page loading screens to disappear. You can see its implementation here:

https://github.com/oppia/oppia/blob/bd43b9dbd3e1680ff9e14223a1ad2f8e0000a827/core/tests/protractor_utils/waitFor.js#L63-L72

It looks like you're trying to wait for the new page to finish loading before exiting this function, but there's no generic way to wait for all async tasks to finish. (side note: protractor normally handles this, but its automatic waiting doesn't work with our hybrid state of both Angular and AngularJS) I think you need the caller of the function to specify what to wait for", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 16, 15, 23, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'U8NWXD', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686985691, 'comment_body': 'I agree "async tasks" is not the correct term as the loading message disappears after fetching the data required for the page from the backend (which doesnot cover all async tasks). Changed the comment', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 16, 21, 20, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686987499, 'comment_body': "Note that we already have a function to wait for url redirection:

https://github.com/oppia/oppia/blob/37c24c46e6fc5a9ee1e8df6fb62d55737fa1ced3/core/tests/protractor_utils/waitFor.js#L140-L144

It's not as generic as your approach though, so I think your approach is fine.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 16, 23, 29, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'U8NWXD', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 686993295, 'comment_body': "I think your updated comment is still not quite right:

>  The above solution only waits until url is changed, so invoking pageToFullyLoad to wait for the new page to load compeletly.

Invoking `pageToFullyLoad` waits for the full-page loading screen to disappear. This does not guarantee that the page has loaded completely for a couple reasons:

1. Not all pages use a full-page loading screen. Some use smaller loading indicators, for example ellipses in the navbar.
2. Even on pages that use a full-page loading screen, the page sometimes hasn't fully loaded even after the screen disappears. For example, the toolbars of rich-text editors sometimes appear after the full-page loading screen disappears.

Basically, `pageToFullyLoad` is an unfortunately-named function that doesn't really wait for the page to be fully loaded. I think the core problem is that since there's no generic way to wait for a page to have fully loaded, this function doesn't have the information it needs to construct an appropriate waitFor statement.

I would suggest one of two approaches:

1. Let the caller specify what to wait for. The caller should know what page comes next and so be able to specify appropriate elements to wait on.
2. Remove the waiting all-together and expect the caller to put waitFor statements after they call your function.

The problem with (2) is that it means that `waitForAngularEnabled(true)` would come before the page has finished loading. I'm not sure if that's okay or not", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 16, 31, 4, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'U8NWXD', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 687015378, 'comment_body': 'Yes, `waitForAngularEnabled(true)` will be called just after the URL changes.
So, there can be a case that browser is still loading javascript bundles and angular is not initialized on the page during the call to waitForAngularEnabled(true). So, we cannot remove waiting.

Made the changes according to first approach.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 11, 17, 1, 30, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'ashutoshc8101', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 687283754, 'comment_body': 'We try to avoid having element selectors in the `protractor_desktop` files. They should instead be in the utility files under `protractor_utils/`. You could create a `waitForPracticeSessionContainer` function in the utility file that gets called here instead', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2021, 8, 12, 0, 34, 51,
